<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-009-373 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 505 356</DOCID><JOURNAL>San Jose Mercury News  Nov 19 1991 p1A(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Congress moves to regulate phone solicitation; bills would create'don't call' registry.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hess, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Congress passes legislation to prevent unwanted telephonesolicitation from people and computers.andP;  The House and Senate passseparate but similar bills that regulate 300,000 companies thatmake unsolicited sales pitches to 18 million people a day.andP;  TheHouse bill, by Rep Edward Markey, D-MA, allows individuals to puttheir names on a 'don't call' list with the Federal CommunicationsCommission.andP;  Any call made to registered numbers would be illegal,and callers would be subject to a $1,500 fine.andP;  The bill wouldalso ban calls dialed automatically by computers, and it wouldcurb the use of fax machines for sending unsolicitedadvertisements.andP;  The legislation exempts charities, politicalparties, pollsters and market research firms.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. CongressTelemarketingGovernment RegulationLegislationAutomatic DialingPrivacy.andO;Person:    Markey, Edward J. (Science and technology policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>